00:02:03.959 --> 00:02:05.959
So, let me be more specific now.

00:02:06.059 --> 00:02:07.059
What's the task?

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:11.660
We're at Epsilon and we have a project with a big pharma company

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:16.160
and the task is to automate a process that accesses a secure data lake.

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:20.759
And this secure data lake contains quite sensitive data.

00:02:20.860 --> 00:02:23.860
There are JXP data about clinical trials.

00:02:24.559 --> 00:02:26.559
There are cancer treatment data

00:02:26.660 --> 00:02:29.460
and even the genome of the patients is in there.

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:33.660
So, what we want to do is to grab some views from there,

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:37.059
some summaries that can be publicly available

00:02:37.559 --> 00:02:40.860
and unload them to an external file storage,

00:02:41.259 --> 00:02:42.860
an AWS S3 bucket.

00:02:43.059 --> 00:02:45.660
This is an efficient cloud storage from AWS.

00:02:46.660 --> 00:02:49.460
And then copy this data to a downstream database

00:02:49.559 --> 00:02:53.759
where we want to do our pre-computation, our optimizations.

00:02:54.259 --> 00:02:56.460
It's a Redshift cluster that we will use.

00:02:57.059 --> 00:03:01.360
And, of course, build downstream applications with Shiny

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:04.559
that we want to be reliable, up-to-date, etc.

00:03:05.860 --> 00:03:09.660
And we will use R and targets as our Swiss army knife

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:12.960
to glue all this together.

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:16.460
So, let's see the requirements in more detail.

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:18.360
We want transparency.

00:03:18.860 --> 00:03:22.460
And by transparency, we mean that whenever this process runs,

00:03:22.559 --> 00:03:24.860
we want to produce some kind of a report

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:30.059
that other people can inspect what happened during this pipeline.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:32.160
We want security.

00:03:32.259 --> 00:03:36.559
And for security here, we have also quite a bit of a constraint

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:40.160
because we are talking about JXP data in a data lake.

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:43.259
Whatever action is performed in the data lake

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:45.960
should be traced back to a particular person.

00:03:46.259 --> 00:03:50.759
So, you cannot blame the robot here if something goes wrong.

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:54.360
We want also automation.

00:03:54.660 --> 00:03:56.860
We want to run this once per day.

00:03:57.960 --> 00:03:59.559
And, of course, we want efficiency.

00:03:59.660 --> 00:04:03.759
And with efficiency, we mean that we have this, our genomic data,

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:05.759
they can go up to billions of rows,

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:07.960
and this process can take hours.

00:04:08.960 --> 00:04:14.960
So, we deployed this pipeline as a Quarto document in PositConnect.

00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:19.859
And PositConnect really served us well in terms of security

00:04:20.459 --> 00:04:26.459
because I can control who can see this process

00:04:26.559 --> 00:04:30.359
and I can specify the users there.

00:04:31.059 --> 00:04:35.059
Also, I can securely store my environmental variables.

00:04:36.059 --> 00:04:38.959
And here, from the UI from PositConnect,

00:04:39.059 --> 00:04:41.260
we can easily store our personal credentials.

00:04:41.359 --> 00:04:44.260
So, now I have this nice synergy

00:04:44.359 --> 00:04:46.660
where I can put my personal credentials there

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:49.660
but control who can run this process.

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:52.859
So, I said that I can run this process only.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:58.260
And all the other people just can see a static HTML

00:04:58.359 --> 00:04:59.859
generated by the process.

00:04:59.959 --> 00:05:02.559
For automation, it's also very easy.

00:05:02.660 --> 00:05:06.160
From the UI, you can see that it is easy to schedule a report,

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:08.160
to run once per day.

00:05:08.859 --> 00:05:13.559
And, of course, reports version, it's very easy to inspect.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:15.959
You can easily go back to history of the reports.

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:19.160
So, PositConnect really served us well

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:22.459
in terms of security and automation.

00:05:22.559 --> 00:05:25.760
And we followed best practices.

00:05:25.859 --> 00:05:28.359
We write our unit tests, our integration tests,

00:05:28.359 --> 00:05:30.260
data validations.

00:05:30.359 --> 00:05:33.260
But something is missing here.

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:36.260
And what about efficiency?

00:05:36.359 --> 00:05:39.260
So, the next day, the pipeline triggers

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:42.260
and everything is computed correctly.

00:05:42.359 --> 00:05:46.260
But do I really want to recompute everything?

00:05:46.359 --> 00:05:49.260
Because, for example, if the inputs have not changed,

00:05:49.359 --> 00:05:54.260
then I already know the results from the previous day.

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:57.160
So, looking closer to PositConnect,

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:00.160
at the bottom line, it is a Cloud Worker.

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:04.160
And the Cloud Worker means that it triggers a process,

00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:06.160
it does some computations,

00:06:06.260 --> 00:06:10.160
and then it writes, of course, some data in the file system.

00:06:10.260 --> 00:06:14.160
But when the Cloud Worker stops, then finishes the process,

00:06:14.260 --> 00:06:18.160
then everything from the file system vanishes.

00:06:18.260 --> 00:06:21.160
So, this means that there is no easy way for me

00:06:22.160 --> 00:06:26.059
and for PositConnect to remember what happened the previous day.

00:06:26.160 --> 00:06:31.059
So, here, we are trapped in a Groundhog Day, right?

00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:36.059
Where you have to live the same day over and over again.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:39.059
And this goes even worse for the development process

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:43.059
because even if I do the slightest change in the pipeline,

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:45.059
I should recompute everything.

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:48.059
And this turns like the Joyful process

00:06:49.059 --> 00:06:50.959
of building a data science workflow

00:06:51.059 --> 00:06:52.959
through a Sisyphean process

00:06:53.059 --> 00:06:56.959
where I have to recompute everything over and over again.

00:06:57.059 --> 00:06:58.959
So, let's see what went wrong here

00:06:59.059 --> 00:07:02.959
and see what options we have to get out of this trap.

00:07:03.059 --> 00:07:05.959
This is a concept from ETL Pipeline.

00:07:06.059 --> 00:07:07.959
It's a very easy concept.

00:07:08.059 --> 00:07:09.959
It's called Directed Acyclic Graph.

00:07:10.059 --> 00:07:12.959
So, consider two inputs, two tables,

00:07:13.059 --> 00:07:14.959
called Data1 and Data2.

00:07:15.959 --> 00:07:18.859
I read this data, I process this data,

00:07:18.959 --> 00:07:20.859
and we join this data.

00:07:20.959 --> 00:07:24.859
And you can see the flow of the logic from the left of the right

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:27.859
and this is a Directed Acyclic Graph.

00:07:27.959 --> 00:07:31.859
I can go now even further and generalize this notion

00:07:31.959 --> 00:07:34.859
where A, B, C, D can be any kind of steps.

00:07:34.959 --> 00:07:37.859
And here, in our case, B can be

00:07:37.959 --> 00:07:41.859
I load some big genomic files to the S3 bucket.

00:07:42.859 --> 00:07:45.760
And I compute some correlation and regression

00:07:45.859 --> 00:07:49.760
in the database for genes that can take hours, et cetera.

00:07:49.859 --> 00:07:53.760
So, what I have created here is an all or nothing scenario.

00:07:53.859 --> 00:07:55.760
And this means that whatever,

00:07:55.859 --> 00:07:57.760
whenever I trigger this pipeline,

00:07:57.859 --> 00:07:59.760
everything is invalidated.

00:07:59.859 --> 00:08:01.760
Everything is processed again.

00:08:01.859 --> 00:08:04.760
And what is the desired behavior?

00:08:04.859 --> 00:08:06.760
So, consider here this G node

00:08:06.859 --> 00:08:09.760
that it is like a kind of a logic

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:14.660
that I just read a small file from the file system

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:16.660
that can take seconds.

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:20.660
And when this file changes, this node is invalidated.

00:08:20.760 --> 00:08:23.660
So, what I want to do is just to recompute

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:27.660
the nodes that are related to this part in my workflow.

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:32.659
And omit the other steps

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:36.659
that can be like big computations that can take hours.

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:40.559
So, going back to my previous experience

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:42.559
from research and data science,

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:44.559
what usually we tend to do

00:08:44.659 --> 00:08:47.559
is like we introduce some kind of an abstraction

00:08:47.659 --> 00:08:51.559
that we call the job or a chapter or something like that.

00:08:51.659 --> 00:08:54.559
And what you tend to do is to break this down

00:08:54.659 --> 00:08:57.559
to some kind of steps that you load some data,

00:08:57.659 --> 00:09:00.559
you process some data, and then you save some data.

00:09:00.659 --> 00:09:04.559
And then you continue on if you want to extend your project.

00:09:05.559 --> 00:09:07.460
You introduce a new job,

00:09:07.559 --> 00:09:11.460
you load some data again, process data, save data.

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:13.460
And this goes on and on,

00:09:13.559 --> 00:09:16.460
and you start creating something like a higher order graph

00:09:16.559 --> 00:09:19.460
where you do things manually.

00:09:19.559 --> 00:09:22.460
But still here you have somehow

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:25.359
breaked out from this Sisyphean cycle

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:27.359
for development process,

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:30.359
but still you have to do some custom scripting

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:33.359
to declare the sequence of jobs.

00:09:33.460 --> 00:09:37.359
You should do some custom scripting to skip steps,

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:40.359
and you should also do some custom scripting,

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:42.359
for example, to shake workflow data.

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:44.359
So, you should be careful.

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:46.359
All the saved files, for example,

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:48.359
if you are in a cloud worker,

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:51.359
to push them to an external file storage.

00:09:51.359 --> 00:09:53.260
That it is persistent.

00:09:53.359 --> 00:09:58.260
And this is just part of a real pipeline in the wild.

00:09:58.359 --> 00:10:00.260
This is a small pipeline,

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:03.260
and these are the components of the pipeline,

00:10:03.359 --> 00:10:05.260
how they are connected together.

00:10:05.359 --> 00:10:07.260
I think you will see in the next presentation

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:09.260
a bigger view of this.

00:10:09.359 --> 00:10:13.260
And do I really want to take up all this complexity?

00:10:13.359 --> 00:10:17.260
Because this now will...

00:10:17.359 --> 00:10:19.260
I'm prone to errors,

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:21.159
and it's much more difficult

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:24.159
to collaborate with other team members.

00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:27.159
This is the chaos I was talking about.

00:10:27.260 --> 00:10:30.159
So, here is where Targets comes into play.

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:33.159
Targets is an opinionated framework

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:37.159
about how to structure your data science workflows

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:39.159
and your data pipelines.

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:42.159
And if you follow its conventions

00:10:42.260 --> 00:10:45.159
and the way that it suggests you to build your workflows,

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:49.159
then you get out of the box many benefits.

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:52.159
Targets will automatically infer

00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:55.159
the directed acyclic graph for you.

00:10:55.260 --> 00:11:00.159
It will strategically skip steps from the pipeline for you.

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:07.159
It will also keep strong reproducible evidence for you.

00:11:07.260 --> 00:11:13.159
And it has great facilities to integrate with cloud storage.

00:11:13.260 --> 00:11:15.159
And of course, it has great facilities

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:18.159
for distributed computing.

00:11:18.159 --> 00:11:21.059
So, how Targets achieve this?

00:11:21.159 --> 00:11:23.059
Targets introduces a simple abstraction

00:11:23.159 --> 00:11:25.059
that it is called a Target.

00:11:25.159 --> 00:11:27.059
And the Target is just a function

00:11:27.159 --> 00:11:29.059
that outputs an object.

00:11:29.159 --> 00:11:31.059
And by convention, this object is pushed

00:11:31.159 --> 00:11:34.059
to your persistent file storage.

00:11:34.159 --> 00:11:38.059
So, let's see a Target script in action.

00:11:38.159 --> 00:11:42.059
These first three lines, we just set the scene.

00:11:42.159 --> 00:11:45.059
So, you load Targets, you set your options,

00:11:45.059 --> 00:11:48.960
and with TarSource, you can load your custom functions.

00:11:49.059 --> 00:11:52.960
And this list is where all the action takes place.

00:11:53.059 --> 00:11:56.960
So, here is where I define my Targets.

00:11:57.059 --> 00:12:01.960
And in this line of code, TarTarget,

00:12:02.059 --> 00:12:04.960
like, declares that this line of code is a Target,

00:12:05.059 --> 00:12:06.960
and then you go to GetData,

00:12:07.059 --> 00:12:09.960
the function that outputs an object,

00:12:10.059 --> 00:12:10.960
the data object.

00:12:11.059 --> 00:12:12.960
So, here we have this duality.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:15.859
GetData function outputs data object.

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:19.859
And then GetData takes as input the file object

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:22.859
that it is generated by a previous Target,

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:25.859
and this goes on and on.

00:12:25.960 --> 00:12:27.859
And Targets will directly infer

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:29.859
the directed acyclic graph for you,

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:32.859
and it will put in the correct order

00:12:32.960 --> 00:12:34.859
all these objects.

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:37.859
So, file now is before data,

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:41.859
and there will be computed correctly.

00:12:41.859 --> 00:12:44.760
Also, Targets has, how we call it,

00:12:44.859 --> 00:12:46.760
Metaflow integration.

00:12:46.859 --> 00:12:48.760
And by Metaflow integration,

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:50.760
we mean that Targets will send

00:12:50.859 --> 00:12:53.760
all this metadata and intermediate files

00:12:53.859 --> 00:12:57.760
that have been computed to a persistent file storage.

00:12:57.859 --> 00:13:00.760
Here we use an S3 bucket,

00:13:00.859 --> 00:13:03.760
so you can just set the options

00:13:03.859 --> 00:13:07.760
and declare your S3 bucket.

00:13:07.859 --> 00:13:10.760
And now you have many benefits.

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:12.659
Some of them are that

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:14.659
you can now scale up to petabytes

00:13:14.760 --> 00:13:16.659
for your storage.

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:19.659
You can just switch on data version control.

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:21.659
And, of course, you have portability.

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:23.659
And by portability, we mean that

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:26.659
this pipeline, you can run this pipeline

00:13:26.760 --> 00:13:28.659
in different machines,

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:31.659
and developers can share cast results

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:32.659
between them.

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:34.659
So, if I have run the pipeline

00:13:34.760 --> 00:13:38.659
and have pre-computed something,

00:13:38.659 --> 00:13:40.559
my colleague can share the cast

00:13:40.659 --> 00:13:46.559
and save hours from his development process.

00:13:46.659 --> 00:13:48.559
Targets has also great facilities

00:13:48.659 --> 00:13:50.559
for distributed computing.

00:13:50.659 --> 00:13:52.559
It uses GRU.

00:13:52.659 --> 00:13:54.559
And it's very easy.

00:13:54.659 --> 00:13:56.559
You just go to the options.

00:13:56.659 --> 00:13:58.559
You set the number of workers.

00:13:58.659 --> 00:14:01.559
Here we set two workers, for example.

00:14:01.659 --> 00:14:04.559
And Targets will start these two workers

00:14:04.659 --> 00:14:08.559
and check if a worker is available.

00:14:08.659 --> 00:14:09.559
As soon as it is available,

00:14:09.659 --> 00:14:13.559
it will send the next target there.

00:14:13.659 --> 00:14:16.559
So here, let's consider a very simple case.

00:14:16.659 --> 00:14:20.559
I have data, some data,

00:14:20.659 --> 00:14:24.559
and I feed two different models with this data.

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:27.559
And this can take, again,

00:14:27.659 --> 00:14:30.559
each model feed can take some time.

00:14:30.659 --> 00:14:33.559
And Targets will check if a worker is available

00:14:33.659 --> 00:14:35.559
and it will send these computations there

00:14:36.559 --> 00:14:39.460
so they are computed in parallel.

00:14:39.559 --> 00:14:41.460
And it has also nice facilities.

00:14:41.559 --> 00:14:43.460
You can also go even further

00:14:43.559 --> 00:14:46.460
to more classic distributed computing,

00:14:46.559 --> 00:14:52.460
like using SAM systems, et cetera.

00:14:52.559 --> 00:14:54.460
For deployment now, it is also very easy.

00:14:54.559 --> 00:14:58.460
You just set in the Quarto document

00:14:58.559 --> 00:15:00.460
one line of code, Target star make,

00:15:00.559 --> 00:15:03.460
and this will trigger the pipeline for you

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:06.359
and will do all these nice things.

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:08.359
So you can automate it easily,

00:15:08.460 --> 00:15:10.359
and pause it, connect.

00:15:10.460 --> 00:15:13.359
And you can also easily read

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:17.359
any previous object that has been computed

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:20.359
and displayed in your report.

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:22.359
